S&P 500 Classification

Fred Viole

07/02/2019

Intro

We are going to define a function for comparing a time-series for its most representative counterpart in a reference time-series(s). This expands the analysis already presented in “Time-Series Classificataion” by using vectors of different lengths for partial time-series matching.

In this example we will ascertain the most similar period for the S&P 500 index since 1950 to the current year 2019 returns through 06-21.

Load Required Packages in R NNS (>= 4.2)

require(devtools); install_github('OVVO-Financial/NNS', ref = "NNS-Beta-Version")
require(NNS)
require(data.table)
require(quantmod)
require(zoo)

Get data

We will load the data for the S&P 500 index from 1950. This will create the variable GSPC. Further, we will create:

  1. A daily return based dataset: current_returns & reference_returns
  2. A dataset of closing prices: current & reference
  3. A window length: w
# Download data
getSymbols('^GSPC', src='yahoo', from=as.Date("1950-01-01"))
## [1] "^GSPC"
# Create reference distribution
reference_returns <- dailyReturn(GSPC) 
reference <- GSPC$GSPC.Adjusted

# Create current distribution (or sub in another period)
current_returns <- reference_returns["2019"]
current <- reference["2019"]

# Window length
w <- length(current_returns)

Which Calendar Year is Most Similar?

Let’s identify the calendar year which is most similar. We will create a series of reference distributions from the beginning of each calendar year of equal length to the current distribution.

returns_list = list()

for(i in seq(1950,2018,1)){
    index <- which(i == seq(1950,2018,1))
    returns_list[[index]] <- reference_returns[as.character(i)][1:w]
}

IV <- matrix(unlist(returns_list), ncol = w, byrow = TRUE)
DV <- seq(1950,2018,1)

nns.estimate <- NNS.reg(IV, DV, point.est = as.numeric(current_returns), order = 'max', n.best = 1, dist = "L2", residual.plot = FALSE)$Point.est
nns.estimate
## [1] 1964
# View the plot on both series
plot(as.zoo(reference[as.character(nns.estimate)][1:w]),lty = 1, col = c("blue"),xlab = "Date",ylab = "Price")
par(new =TRUE)
plot(as.zoo(current),screens = 1,lty = 5, col = "red",xlab = "",ylab = "", xaxt = "n", yaxt = "n")
axis(4)
mtext("Price", side = 4, line = 3)
legend("topleft",c("Reference","Current (RHS)"),lty = c(1,1),col = c("blue","red"),cex = 0.5)

# Future from most similar period
future_GSPC <- reference[as.character(nns.estimate)][w:(2*w)]
plot(future_GSPC)

Finding the Most Similar Period (Non-Calendar Year)

Next we will eschew the calendar year and scan overlapping years to find the most similar period. The independent variable matrices get excessive (since each observation is an IV and they sequentially overlap), so we can simplify by minimizing the sum-of-squared differences, or maximizing the linear correlation of vectors to determine similarity.

Remove current period, also a verification of similarity!

If we do not remove the last w observations from the reference data, we will match exactly to the current starting period, 01-02-2019.

custom_cor <- function(x,y){
  #a <- sum(as.numeric(x)>0 & as.numeric(y)>0 | as.numeric(x)<0 & as.numeric(y)<0)/length(x)
  a <- cor(as.numeric(x), as.numeric(y))
  return(a)
}

# Remove current period (look what we get if we don't!!!)
best.period.1 <- which.max( rollapply( seq_along(reference_returns), width = w, function(i)  custom_cor(reference_returns[i], current_returns) ) )

GSPC[best.period.1]
##            GSPC.Open GSPC.High GSPC.Low GSPC.Close GSPC.Volume
## 2019-01-02   2476.96   2519.49  2467.47    2510.03  3733160000
##            GSPC.Adjusted
## 2019-01-02       2510.03

Yup, exact match! Let’s remove those current observations from the reference.

reference <- head(reference, length(reference)-w)
reference_returns <- head(reference_returns, length(reference_returns)-w)

Method 1: Linear Correlation and Normalized Returns Data

The first method we will use is a regular linear correlation of the daily returns data.

best.period.1 <- which.max( rollapply( seq_along(reference_returns), width = w, function(i)  custom_cor(reference_returns[i], current_returns) ) )

# Most smilar period
GSPC[c(best.period.1, best.period.1+w)]
##            GSPC.Open GSPC.High GSPC.Low GSPC.Close GSPC.Volume
## 2016-06-24   2103.81   2103.81  2032.57    2037.41  7597450000
## 2016-12-21   2270.54   2271.23  2265.15    2265.18  2852230000
##            GSPC.Adjusted
## 2016-06-24       2037.41
## 2016-12-21       2265.18
# View Plot on Both Series
plot(as.zoo(reference[best.period.1:(best.period.1+w)]),lty = 1, col = c("blue"),xlab = "Date",ylab = "Price")
par(new =TRUE)
plot(as.zoo(current),screens = 1,lty = 5, col = "red",xlab = "",ylab = "", xaxt = "n", yaxt = "n")
axis(4)
mtext("Price", side = 4, line = 3)
legend("topleft",c("Reference","Current (RHS)"),lty = c(1,1),col = c("blue","red"),cex = 0.5)

# Future from most similar period
GSPC[c(best.period.1+w,best.period.1+(2*w))]
##            GSPC.Open GSPC.High GSPC.Low GSPC.Close GSPC.Volume
## 2016-12-21   2270.54   2271.23  2265.15    2265.18  2852230000
## 2017-06-22   2437.40   2441.62  2433.27    2434.50  3468210000
##            GSPC.Adjusted
## 2016-12-21       2265.18
## 2017-06-22       2434.50
future_GSPC_1 <- reference[(best.period.1+w):(best.period.1+(2*w))]
plot(future_GSPC_1)

# SSE
sum( (as.numeric(reference_returns[best.period.1:(best.period.1-1+w)]) - as.numeric(current_returns))^2 )
## [1] 0.0092159

Method 2: Sum-of-Squared Differences of Daily Returns

The second method again uses the daily returns, but will sum their squared differences.

Accuracy Check

First, let’s check its accuracy on the complete dataset to see if it selects 01-02-2019 as the most likely period…

reference_returns <- dailyReturn(GSPC)

best.period.2 <- which.min(rollapply(seq_along(reference_returns), width = w, function(i)  sum( (as.numeric(reference_returns[i])-as.numeric(current_returns))^2 ) ) )


# Most smilar period
GSPC[best.period.2]
##            GSPC.Open GSPC.High GSPC.Low GSPC.Close GSPC.Volume
## 2019-01-02   2476.96   2519.49  2467.47    2510.03  3733160000
##            GSPC.Adjusted
## 2019-01-02       2510.03

Yup, it works!

Apply Sum-of-Squared Differences to Daily Returns

Now we will apply the sum-of-squared differences to the daily returns data, after removing the current observations from the reference…again.

reference_returns <- head(reference_returns, length(reference_returns)-w)

best.period.2 <- which.min( rollapply( seq_along(reference_returns), width = w, function(i)  sum( (as.numeric(reference_returns[i])-as.numeric(current_returns))^2 ) ) )


# Most smilar period
GSPC[c(best.period.2, best.period.2+w)]

Comments

  • Evaluating each of the methods most similar daily returns via the minimum sum-of-squared errors, reveals Method #2 has the best fit.
  • We have not ventured far into the definition of \(similar\). We have demonstrated 2 methods of determining similarity, and unfortunately, the future outcomes are substantially varied based on the definition and evaluation criteria.
  • Based on prevailing evaluation criteria, both future outcomes are significantly positive from current levels for the next 125 day period
# View Plot on Both Series
plot(as.zoo(future_GSPC_1),lty = 1, col = c("blue"), xlab = "Date", ylab = "Price")
par(new =TRUE)
plot(as.zoo(future_GSPC_2),screens = 1,lty = 5, col = "red", xlab = "", ylab = "", xaxt = "n", yaxt = "n")
axis(4)
mtext("Price", side = 4, line = 3)
legend("topleft", c("Future via Method #1 (LHS)","Future via Method #2 (RHS)"), lty = c(1,1), col = c("blue","red"), cex = 0.5)

Edit (07-02-2019)

Per comments, I have included the binary classification of the most similar period and a dynamic time warping. The binary classification is simply the percentage of concordant tuples sum(x<0 & y<0 | x>0 & y>0) / length(x). First, we will check their accuracy.

custom_cor_2 <- function(x,y){
  a <- sum(as.numeric(x)>0 & as.numeric(y)>0 | as.numeric(x)<0 & as.numeric(y)<0)/length(x)
  return(a)
}

require(TSdist)



reference_returns <- dailyReturn(GSPC)

best.period.3 <- which.max(rollapply(seq_along(reference_returns), width = w, function(i)  custom_cor_2(reference_returns[i], current_returns) ) )



# Most smilar period
GSPC[best.period.3]
##            GSPC.Open GSPC.High GSPC.Low GSPC.Close GSPC.Volume
## 2019-01-02   2476.96   2519.49  2467.47    2510.03  3733160000
##            GSPC.Adjusted
## 2019-01-02       2510.03
best.period.4 <- which.min(rollapply(seq_along(reference_returns), width = w, function(i)  DTWDistance(reference_returns[i], current_returns) ) )
